{{flagicon|Netherlands}} || {{birth date and age|1999|10|8|df=y}} || Right-handed || Right-arm [[Fast bowling|medium]]  || style=\"text-align:center;\"| 2021 || style=\"text-align:right;\"| ||||Overseas\n|-\n|70|| '''[[Reniece Boyce]]''' || style=\"text-align:center\"|{{flagicon|TRI}} || {{birth date and age|1997|9|3|df=y}} || Right-handed || Right-arm [[Fast bowling|medium]]  || style=\"text-align:center;\"| 2021 || style=\"text-align:right;\"| ||||Overseas\n|-\n|28|| '''[[Taniya Bhatia]]''' || style=\"text-align:center\"|{{flagicon|IND}} || {{birth date and age|1997|11|28|df=y}} || Right-handed || Right-arm [[leg break]]  || style=\"text-align:center;\"| 2021 || style=\"text-align:right;\"| ||||\n|-\n|66|| '''[[Sarah Bryce]]''' || style=\"text-align:center\"|{{flagicon|SCO}} || {{birth date and age|2000|1|8|df=y}} || Right-handed || Right-arm [[Fast bowling|medium]]  || style=\"text-align:center;\"| 2021 || style=\"text-align:right;\"| ||||Overseas\n|-\n! colspan=\"10\"  style=\"background:#dcdcdc; text-align:center;\"| Bowlers\n|-\n|68|| [[Sushree Dibyadarshini]] || style=\"text-align:center\"|{{flagicon|IND}} || {{birth date and age|1997|9|8|df=y}} || Right-handed || Right-arm [[off break]] || style=\"text-align:center;\"| 2021 || style=\"text-align:right;\"| |||| \n|-\n|21|| '''[[Radha Yadav]]''' || style=\"text-align:center\"|{{flagicon|IND}} || {{birth date and age|2000|4|21|df=y}} || Right-handed || [[Slow left-arm orthodox]] || style=\"text-align:center;\"| 2021 || style=\"text-align:right;\"| ||||\n|-\n|11|| '''[[Pooja Vastrakar]]''' || style=\"text-align:center\"|{{flagicon|IND}} || {{birth date and age|1999|9|25|df=y}} || Right-handed || Right-arm [[medium]] || style=\"text-align:center;\"| 2021 || style=\"text-align:right;\"| ||||\n|-\n|92|| '''[[Raisibe Ntozakhe]]''' || style=\"text-align:center\"|{{flagicon|RSA}} || {{birth date and age|1996|11|29|df=y}} || Right-handed || Right-arm [[off break]] || style=\"text-align:center;\"| 2021 || style=\"text-align:right;\"| |||| Overseas\n|-\n|15|| [[Manali Dakshini]] || style=\"text-align:center\"|{{flagicon|IND}} || {{birth date and age|1997|9|29|df=y}} || Right-handed ||Right-arm [[medium]] || style=\"text-align:center;\"| 2021 || style=\"text-align:right;\"| ||||\n|-\n|20|| '''[[Arundhati Reddy]]''' || style=\"text-align:center\"|{{flagicon|IND}} || {{birth date and age|1997|10|4|df=y}} || Right-handed || Right-arm [[Fast bowling|medium-fast]] || style=\"text-align:center;\"| 2021 || style=\"text-align:right;\"|  ||  ||\n|}\n\n{{notelist}}\n\n==Administration and support staff==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"  style=\"font-size:85%; width:55%;\"\n|-\n! style=\"background:; color:; text-align:center;\"| Position\n! style=\"background:; color:; -align:center;\"| Name\n|-\n|Director of cricket operations||{{flagicon|IND}} [[Sulakshana Naik]]\n|-\n|Head coach || {{flagicon|SRI}} [[Prasadani Weerakkody]]\n|-\n|Assistant coach||{{flagicon|NZL}} [[Haidee Tiffen]]\n|-\n|Batting coach ||{{flagicon|ENG}} [[Lydia Greenway]]\n|-\n|Batting mentor|| {{flagicon|AUS}} [[Alex Blackwell]]\n|-\n|Spin bowling coach || {{flagicon|IND}} [[Neetu David]]\n|-\n|Spin bowling mentor || {{flagicon|IND}} [[Nooshin Al Khadeer]]\n|-\n|Fast bowling coach|| {{flagicon|RSA}} [[Ashlyn Kilowan]]\n|-\n|Fast Bowling mentor||{{flagicon|IND}} [[Jhulan Goswami]]\n|-\n|Fielding coach||{{flagicon|IND}} [[Ekta Bisht]]\n|-\n|Talent Scouts||{{flagicon|Netherlands}} [[Esther Lanser]], {{flagicon|IND}} [[Nidhi Buley]], {{flagicon|PAK}} [[Almas Akram]], {{flagicon|IND}} [[Amita Sharma]],  {{flagicon|IND}} [[Reema Malhotra]], {{flagicon|IND}} [[Preeti Dimri]]\n|-\n|Wicket keeping coach||{{flagicon|TRI}} [[Merissa Aguilleira]]\n|-\n|Assistant wicket keeping coach||{{flagicon|IRE}} [[Meg Kendal]]\n|-\n|Right arm throwdown specialist||{{flagicon|SCO}} [[Kari Anderson]]\n|-\n|Left arm throwdown specialist||{{flagicon|NEP}} [[Nary Thapa]]\n|-\n|Physiotherapist||{{flagicon|IND}} Tracy Fernandes\n|-\n|Assistant physiotherapist||{{flagicon|IND}} Anuja Dalvi Pandit\n|-\n|Strength and conditioning coach||{{flagicon|IND}} Benafsha Gazdar\n|-\n|Assistant trainer||{{flagicon|IND}} Chaitra Khanvilkar\n|-\n|Assistant trainer||{{flagicon|IND}} Apoorva Nadkarni\n|-\n|Analyst|| {{flagicon|IND}} Aarti Nalge\n|-\n|Nutritionist||{{flagicon|IND}} A Nirusha\n|-\n|Massage therapist||{{flagicon|IND}} Shalini Chaudary\n|-\n|Team doctor||{{flagicon|IND}} Dr. Sireesha Anne\n|-\n|Psychologist|| {{flagicon|IND}} Dr. Chaitanya Sridhar\n|-\n|Yoga instructor|| {{flagicon|IND}} Sujitha Selvaraj\n|-\n|}\n\n==Sponsorship==\nAs of 2021,[[Nike]] to manufacture kits for the team,[[Ramoji Group|Ramoji]] became the principal sponsor.[[Raymond Group|Raymond]],[[GVK (conglomerate)|GVK]] were the associate sponsors.Other official partners included [[Aura Thai Spa]],[[Anytime Fitness]],[[Sareen Sports Industries]],[[INOX Leisure Limited|INOX]] [[Vizag]].\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"  style=\"font-size:85%; width:55%;\"\n|- \n! style=\"width:15%;background:; color:;\"|Year\n! style=\"width:13%;background:; color:;\"|Kit manufacturer\n! style=\"width:13%;background:; color:;\"|Sponsor (main)\n! style=\"width:13%;background:; color:;\"|Sponsor (back)\n! style=\"width:13%;background:; color:;\"|Sponsor (chest)\n! style=\"width:13%;background:; color:;\"|Sponsor (sleeve)\n! style=\"width:13%;background:; color:;\"|Sponsor (cap)\n! style=\"width:13%;background:; color:;\"|Sponsor (pant)\n! style=\"width:13%;background:; color:;\"|Other sponsors\n|-\n|2021\n|[[Nike]]\n|[[Ramoji Group|Ramoji]]\n|[[Raymond Group|Raymond]]\n|[[GVK (conglomerate)|GVK]]\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|}\n==Kit manufacturers and sponsors==\n[[Federal Bank]], a major Indian commercial bank in the private sector, with headquarters in [[Aluva]], Kerala, was the principal sponsor of Kochi Tuskers Kerala.<ref name=\"newindianexpress1\"/> The tickets for KTK's home matches were sold through Federal bank branches and their website. The Ticket sales of Kochi Tuskers Kerala was officially started in a ceremony hosted at the Le Meridian Hotel Kochi, on 28 March. Soon after, the tickets become available at the team's official ticketing partner website [[Kyazoonga|kyazoonga.com]].<ref name=\"kochiservnet1\"/>\n\n[[Lotto Sport Italia|Lotto]], an Italian sports goods manufacturer was the apparel sponsor for the team.<ref name=\"indiatimes1\"/>\n\n[[V-Guard]], an electronics company and AVT, a tea brand were the associate sponsors.\n[[Elite Foods]], [[Parinee Developers]] and [[Anchor Earth]] are the other main sponsors.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|- \n! style=\"width:15%;background:orange; color:purple;\"|Year\n! style=\"width:13%;background:orange; color:purple;\"|Kit manufacturer\n! style=\"width:13%;background:orange; color:purple;\"|Shirt sponsor (chest)\n! style=\"width:13%;background:orange; color:purple;\"|Shirt sponsor (back)\n! style=\"width:13%;background:orange; color:purple;\"|Chest Branding\n|-\n|2011\n|[[Lotto Sport Italia|Lotto]]\n|'''Anchor Toothpaste'''\n|[[Federal Bank]]\n|'''Parinee Developers'''\n|}\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of controversies involving the Indian Premier League]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category}}\n*{{Official website|http://www.kochituskerskerala.com/}}\n* [http://www.espncricinfo.com/ipl-kochi/content/team/474668.html KTK Cricinfo]\n*[http://www.facebook.com/TuskersKochi IPL Team Page]\n{{Indian Premier League}}\n\n[[Category:Kochi Tuskers Kerala|*]]\n[[Category:Indian Premier League teams]]\n[[Category:Sport in Kochi]]\n[[Category:Sports clubs in India]]\n[[Category:Cricket clubs established in 2010]]\n[[Category:Sports clubs disestablished in 2011]]\n[[Category:2011 disestablishments in India]]\n[[Category:Former senior cricket clubs of India]]\n[[Category:Cricket in Kerala]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toNike(link changed toNike, Inc.; link changed toNike, Inc.) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kochi_Tuskers_Kerala"}
{"title_page": "Health effects arising from the September 11 attacks", "text_new": "{{Pp-semi-indef}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2014}}\n[[File:Manhattan smoke plume on September 11, 2001 from International Space Station (Expedition 3 crew).jpg|thumb|350px|[[International Space Station]] image taken on September 11, 2001, with the smoke plume rising from [[Lower Manhattan]] and extending over [[Brooklyn]] ([[Expedition 3]] crew)]]\nThere has been growing concern over the '''health effects arising from the [[September 11 attacks]]''' in the [[Financial District, Manhattan|Financial District]] of [[Lower Manhattan]]. Within seconds of the [[collapse of the World Trade Center]], building materials, electronic equipment, and furniture were pulverized and spread over the area.\n\nIn the five months following the attacks, dust from the pulverized buildings continued to fill the air of the [[World Trade Center site]]. Increasing numbers of New York residents are reporting symptoms of Ground Zero [[respiratory illness]]es.<ref name=\"latimes3275974\">{{cite news| url=https://articles.latimes.com/2006/oct/14/nation/na-cleaners14 | work=Los Angeles Times | title=Lost in the Dust of 9/11 | first=Ellen | last=Barry | date=October 14, 2006 | accessdate=May 4, 2010}}</ref>\n\nVarious health programs have arisen to deal with the ongoing health effects of the September 11 attacks. The [[World Trade Center Health Program]], which provides testing and treatment to 9/11 responders and survivors, consolidated many of these after the [[James Zadroga 9/11 Health and Compensation Act]] became law in January 2011.<ref name=\"WTCHP faq\">{{cite web|title=World Trade Center Health Program FAQ|url=https://www.cdc.gov/wtc/faq.html|publisher=Centers for Disease Control and Prevention|accessdate=July 2, 2012}}</ref>\n\n== Exposures and conditions ==\n{{More medical citations needed|section|date=January 2018}}\nAs of December 2017, the most common conditions certified by the [[World Trade Center Health Program]] were [[rhinosinusitis]], [[gastroesophageal reflux disease]] (GERD), [[asthma]], [[sleep apnea]], [[cancer]], [[posttraumatic stress disorder]], [[respiratory disease]], [[chronic obstructive pulmonary disease]], [[Depression (mood)|depression]], and [[anxiety disorder]].  The most common cancers were [[skin cancer]] and [[prostate cancer]].  The [[World Trade Center Health Program]] regularly publishes the most commonly certified condition on its website.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cdc.gov/wtc/ataglance.html#top10Conditions|title=Program Statistics - World Trade Center Health Program|website=www.cdc.gov|language=en|access-date=2018-01-30}}</ref>[[File:Manhattan on September 12 - Landsat7.jpg|thumb|250px|left|September 12 from space: Manhattan spreads a large smoke plume]]\n\n=== Toxic dust ===\n[[File:9-11 Research - What are we Finding Related to Airway Injury to Patients Exposed to WTC Dust.webm|thumb|A video on airway injury in patients exposed to WTC dust]]\nThe dust from the collapsed towers was \"wildly toxic\", according to air pollution expert and [[University of California Davis]] Professor Emeritus Thomas Cahill.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/money/industries/health/2006-06-25-911-health-usat_x.htm|title=9/11 Health Troubles?|last=Armour|first=Stephanie|date=June 25, 2006|work=USA Today|accessdate=May 4, 2010}}</ref> Much of the thousands of tons of debris resulting from the collapse of the Twin Towers was pulverized concrete, which is known to cause [[silicosis]] upon inhalation. The remainder consisted of more than 2,500 contaminants,<ref name=\"anitagates\">Anita Gates, \"Buildings Rise from Rubble while Health Crumbles\", ''The New York Times'', September 11, 2006, reporting on the documentary by Heidi Dehncke-Fisher, \"Dust to Dust: The Health Effects of 9/11\"</ref> more specifically: 50% non-fibrous material and construction debris; 40%&nbsp;glass and other fibers; 9.2%&nbsp;cellulose; and 0.8% of the extremely toxic carcinogen [[asbestos]], as well as detectable amounts of<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/imagepages/2006/09/05/nyregion/20060905_HEALTH_GRAPHIC.html|title=What was Found in the Dust|date=September 5, 2006|work=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=2006-09-08}}</ref> [[lead (element)|lead]] and [[Mercury (element)|mercury]]. There were also unprecedented levels of [[Dioxins and dioxin-like compounds|dioxins]] and [[Polycyclic aromatic hydrocarbon|PAHs]] from the fires which burned for three months.<ref>Dr. Dennis Charney, in the September 2006 edition of ''Environmental Health Perspectives'', the journal of the National Institute of Environmental Health Sciences</ref> Many of the dispersed substances (asbestos, crystalline silica, lead, cadmium, polycyclic aromatic hydrocarbons) are [[carcinogenic]]; other substances can trigger kidney, heart, liver and nervous system deterioration. This was well known by the EPA at the time of collapse.<ref name=\"anitagates\" /> A case report funded by the [[National Institute for Occupational Safety and Health]] (NIOSH) and  performed by [[Mount Sinai School of Medicine]] observed [[carbon nanotubes]] in dust samples and in the lungs of several 9/11 responders.<ref>{{cite journal|displayauthors=etal|year=2009|title=Case Report: Lung Disease in World Trade Center Responders Exposed to Dust and Smoke: Carbon Nanotubes Found in the Lungs of World Trade Center Patients and Dust Samples|journal=Environmental Health Perspectives|volume=118|issue=4|pages=499\u2013504|doi=10.1289/ehp.0901159|pmc=2854726|pmid=20368128|author=Wu M|name-list-format=vanc|author2=Gordon RE|author3=Herbert R|author4=Padilla M|author5=Moline J}}</ref> The understanding of the smoke and dust in the air was not fully understood at the time; the [[World Trade Center Health Program|World Trade Center Health Program's]] Dr. Michael Crane touched upon this issue in an interview with ''Newsweek'' stating:<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nymag.com/intelligencer/2016/09/15-years-later-how-has-9-11-affected-new-yorkers-health.html|title=What We Know About How 9/11 Has Affected New Yorkers' Health, 15 Years Later|last=Bankoff|first=Caroline|website=Intelligencer|language=en|access-date=2019-06-04}}</ref>\n\n{{Quote|text=\u201cWe will never know the composition of that cloud, because the wind carried it away, but people were breathing and eating it...What we do know is that it had all kinds of god-awful things in it. Burning jet fuel. Plastics, metal, fiberglass, asbestos. It was thick, terrible stuff. A witch\u2019s brew.\u201d|sign=World Trade Center Health Program's Dr. Michael Crane|source=Newsweek Interview}}\n\nThese toxic exposures have led to debilitating illnesses among rescue, recovery, and cleanup workers, and the [[pulmonary fibrosis]] death of NYPD member Cesar Borja.<ref name=\"richschapiro\">{{cite news|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/front/story/408217p-345459c.html|title=WTC air doomed ex-cop|date=April 12, 2006|publisher=New York Daily News|author=Schapiro, Rich|accessdate=2006-09-08|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060906154357/http://www.nydailynews.com/front/story/408217p-345459c.html|archivedate=September 6, 2006|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"sonsname\">NOTE: son's name spelt differently -ASSOCIATED PRESS, Bush May Meet With Dead Officer's Son, ''The New York Times'', January 30, 2007</ref><ref name=\"carlcampanile-kinsuing\">Carl Campanile, \"Kin Suing City over 'WTC toxin' Death\" \"New York Post\" January 29, 2007, p. 2</ref><ref>Jeff Stier, \"The Mystery of Lung Disease\", ''New York Sun', February 20, 2007''</ref> Increasing numbers of cases are appearing in which first responders are developing serious respiratory ailments.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/05/13/nyregion/13symptoms.html?_r=1&oref=slogin|title=Tracing Lung Ailments That Rose With 9/11 Dust|last=Depalma|first=Anthony|date=May 13, 2006|work=The New York Times|accessdate=May 4, 2010}}</ref> Health effects also extended to some residents, students, and office workers of Lower Manhattan and nearby [[Chinatown, Manhattan|Chinatown]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sierraclub.org/groundzero/ |title=Updated Ground Zero Report Examines Failure of Government to Protect Citizens |year=2006 |publisher=Sierra Club |accessdate=2006-09-08 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100611191219/http://www.sierraclub.org/groundzero/ |archivedate=June 11, 2010 |df= }}</ref>\n\nDr. Edwin M. Kilbourne, a high level federal scientist, issued a memo on September 12, 2001, to the [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] advising against the speedy return to buildings in the area because of possible hazards from various toxic materials.<ref name=\"juangonzalez\">Juan Gonzalez, \"Clearing the Air with Truth\", ''New York Daily News'', September 5, 2001.</ref>\n\nAssociate City Health Commissioner Kelly McKinney on October 6, 2001, said that proper safety protocol for WTC site workers was not being enforced.<ref name=\"juangonzalez\" />\n\nA study of 5,000 rescue workers published in April 2010 by Dr. David J. Prezant the chief medical officer for the Office of Medical Affairs at the New York City Fire Department found that all the workers studied had impaired lung functions with an average impairment of 10 percent. The study found the impairments presented itself in the first year of after the attack with little or no improvements in the ensuing six years. 30 to 40 percent of workers were reporting persistent symptoms and 1000 of the group studied were on \"permanent respiratory disability.\" Dr. Prezant noted the medications that are being given ease symptoms but are not a cure. Dr. Byron Thomashow, medical director of the Center for Chest Disease and Respiratory Failure at New York\u2013Presbyterian/Columbia hospital said that \"The drop-off in lung function initially is really quite significant and doesn't get better. That's not what we've generally come to expect in people with fire and smoke exposure. They usually recover.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/04/08/nyregion/08lung.html|title=Lung Function of 9/11 Rescuers Fell, Study Finds|last=Grady|first=Denise|date=2010-04-07|newspaper=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=2016-11-16}}</ref>\n\n===Cancer risk===\n[[File:9-11 Research - What are the Three Types of Cancer Found to Increase in WTC Exposed Populations.webm|thumb|A video on the three types of cancer found to increase in WTC exposed populations]]\nA study published in December 2012 in [[JAMA (journal)|''The Journal of the American Medical Association'']] observed the possible association between exposure to the World Trade Center debris and excess cancer risk. Over 55,000 individuals enrolled in the World Trade Center Health Registry, separated by rescue and/or recovery workers and non-rescue and/or recovery workers, were observed from 2003 or 2004 to December 31, 2008. The findings showed the overall [[incidence (epidemiology)|incidence]] of all cancers among rescue and/or recovery workers was not significantly elevated, compared to non-rescue and/or recovery workers. Despite this, the incidences for [[prostate cancer]], [[thyroid cancer]], and [[multiple myeloma]] were significantly elevated among the rescue and/or recovery workers, in the final year of observation.<ref name=\"Li\">{{cite journal|last2=Cone|first2=JE|last3=Kahn|first3=AR|last4=Brackbill|first4=RM|last5=Farfel|first5=MR|last6=Greene|first6=CM|last7=Hadler|first7=JL|last8=Stayner|first8=LT|last9=Stellman|first9=SD|year=2012|title=Association between World Trade Center exposure and excess cancer risk|journal=JAMA|publisher=American Medical Association|volume=308|issue=23|pages=2479\u201388|doi=10.1001/jama.2012.110980|pmid=23288447|last1=Li|first1=J}}</ref>\n\nOn November 28, 2006, the ''[[Village Voice]]'' reported that several dozen recovery personnel have developed cancer \u2013 as opposed to having contracted respiratory ailments, and that doctors have argued that some of these cancers developed as a result of the exposure to toxins at the Ground Zero site:\n\"To date, 75 recovery workers at ground zero have been diagnosed with blood cell cancers that a half-dozen top doctors and epidemiologists have confirmed as having been likely caused by that exposure.\"<ref name=\"kristenlombardi\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.villagevoice.com/news/death-by-dust-6429304|title=Death by Dust|last=Lombardi|first=Kristen|date=2006-11-21|newspaper=Village Voice|access-date=2016-11-16}}</ref>\n\nOn September 11, 2018, 17 years after the attacks, a New York City law firm reported that at least 15 men were diagnosed with male breast cancer in the intervening years due to the attacks.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/at-least-15-men-near-ground-zero-after-911-have-breast-cancer-law-firm-says/ |title=At least 15 men near Ground Zero after 9/11 have breast cancer, law firm says |last=Welch |first=Ashley |publisher=CBS News |date=September 11, 2018 |access-date=September 12, 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Psychological effects ===\n[[File:9-11 Research - What is the Risk of WTC Responders Developing PTSD as a Result of 9 11 Exposures.webm|thumb|A video on the risk of developing posttraumatic stress disorder as a result of 9/11 exposures]]\nA study published two months after 9/11 found that Americans across the country experienced substantial symptoms of stress after the attacks.<ref>{{cite journal|last2=Stein|first2=Bradley D.|last3=Jaycox|first3=Lisa H.|last4=Collins|first4=Rebecca L.|last5=Marshall|first5=Grant N.|last6=Elliott|first6=Marc N.|last7=Zhou|first7=Annie J.|last8=Kanouse|first8=David E.|last9=Morrison|first9=Janina L.|date=15 November 2001|title=A National Survey of Stress Reactions after the September 11, 2001, Terrorist Attacks|journal=New England Journal of Medicine|volume=345|issue=20|pages=1507\u20131512|doi=10.1056/NEJM200111153452024|pmid=11794216|last1=Schuster|first1=Mark A.|last10=Berry|first10=Sandra H.}}</ref> Two subsequent studies found that exposure to the attacks was a predictor of the development of [[PTSD]].<ref>{{cite journal|last2=Caddell|first2=Juesta M.|last3=Ebert|first3=Lori|last4=Jordan|first4=B. Kathleen|last5=Rourke|first5=Kathryn M.|last6=Wilson|first6=David|last7=Thalji|first7=Lisa|last8=Dennis|first8=J. Michael|last9=Fairbank|first9=John A.|date=7 August 2002|title=Psychological Reactions to Terrorist Attacks|journal=JAMA|volume=288|issue=5|pages=581\u20138|doi=10.1001/jama.288.5.581|pmid=12150669|last1=Schlenger|first1=William E.|last10=Kulka|first10=Richard A.}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last2=Ahern|first2=Jennifer|last3=Resnick|first3=Heidi|last4=Kilpatrick|first4=Dean|last5=Bucuvalas|first5=Michael|last6=Gold|first6=Joel|last7=Vlahov|first7=David|date=28 March 2002|title=Psychological Sequelae of the September 11 Terrorist Attacks in New York City|journal=New England Journal of Medicine|volume=346|issue=13|pages=982\u2013987|doi=10.1056/NEJMsa013404|pmid=11919308|last1=Galea|first1=Sandro|hdl=2027.42/40334}}</ref>\n\n===Reactions===\nDr. Larry Norton of [[Memorial Sloan-Kettering Hospital]] said \"Why isn't the whole nation mobilizing to take care of the chronic health impact of this disaster?\". Dr. Norton cited the 70&nbsp;percent illness rate among first responders as \"a wake up call.\" Dr. Nathaniel Hupert of [[Weill Cornell Medical College]], quoted by Jill Gardiner of the October 4, 2006, issue of the ''[[New York Sun]]'' said that premature deaths and other ailments of dogs in the area are \"our canary in the coalmine.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nysun.com/article/40891|title=Top Doctors Say Trade Center Dust Could Cause Cancer|accessdate=June 15, 2015}}</ref>\nRichard Clapp and David Ozonoff, professors of environmental health at [[Boston University School of Public Health]]; Michael Thun, director of epidemiological research at the [[American Cancer Society]]; Francine Laden, assistant professor of environmental [[epidemiology]] at [[Harvard School of Public Health]]; Jonathan Samet, chairman of the epidemiology department at [[Johns Hopkins Bloomberg School of Public Health]]; and Charles Hesdorffer, associate professor of oncology at [[Johns Hopkins School of Medicine]] argue that the cancer incidence among monitored individuals cannot be called a coincidence. They assert that the Ground Zero cloud was likely the cause of the illnesses.<ref name=\"kristenlombardi\" /> The American College of Preventative Medicine is concerned that malignant [[mesothelioma]] will develop among persons exposed to Ground Zero air.<ref>BBC News online Friday, April 26, 2002, 16:19 GMT 17:19 UK \"Ground Zero cancer fears\"</ref>\n\n== Monitoring ==\nThere is scientific speculation that exposure to various toxic products and the pollutants in the air surrounding the Towers after the WTC collapse may have negative effects on fetal development. Due to this potential hazard, a notable children's environmental health center (Columbia University Center for Children's Health) is currently analyzing the children whose mothers were pregnant during the WTC collapse, and were living or working near the World Trade Center towers. The staff of this study assesses the children using psychological testing every year and interviews the mothers every six months. The purpose of the study is to determine whether there is significant difference in development and health progression of children whose mothers were exposed, versus those who were not exposed after the WTC collapse.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cpmcnet.columbia.edu/dept/sph/ccceh/research/wtc_pregnancy.html|title=CCCEH Study of the Effects of 9/11 on Pregnant Women and Newborns|year=2006|publisher=Columbia University|work=World Trade Center Pregnancy Study|accessdate=2006-09-08|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060910090040/http://cpmcnet.columbia.edu/dept/sph/ccceh/research/wtc_pregnancy.html|archivedate=September 10, 2006|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n[[Mount Sinai Hospital, New York|Mount Sinai Medical Center]] is conducting an ongoing monitoring program, World Trade Center Worker and Volunteer Medical Screening Program.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wtcexams.org|title=World Trade Center Health Program - The Mount Sinai Hospital|work=The Mount Sinai Hospital|accessdate=June 15, 2015}}</ref>\nA leader of Mt. Sinai monitoring efforts is Stephen M. Levin, Medical Director of the Mount Sinai \u2013 Irving J. Selikoff Center for Occupational and Environmental Medicine.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://epw.senate.gov/107th/Levin_021102.htm|title=Testimony of Stephen Levin, Feb. 11, 2002|accessdate=June 15, 2015}}</ref> First responders met in a conference, November 11, 2006, in an effort to monitor responders' health. The event was organized by the World Trade Center Monitoring Program.<ref name=\"twfarnam\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.newsday.com/news/health/ny-nywtcvr4972450nov12%2C0%2C7496420.story?coll=ny-health-print |title=9/11 responders seek options for care - Newsday.com |date=2006-11-14 |access-date=2016-11-16 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061114012959/http://www.newsday.com/news/health/ny-nywtcvr4972450nov12%2C0%2C7496420.story?coll=ny-health-print |archivedate=November 14, 2006 }}</ref>\n\nAn ongoing [[Pennsylvania State University]]/[[Monmouth University]] study reported that [[respiratory]] illnesses grew by more than two hundred percent in the year and a half after the September 11 attacks. (This was the first study that monitored police officers at the Ground Zero site. It was published in the \"Journal of Occupational and Environmental Medicine.\") In this study of 471 police officers, 19 percent of the officers in October 2001 experienced shortness of breath; 44 percent of the officers experienced shortness of breath in April 2003. The percentage of the 471 officers coughing up [[phlegm]] increased from 14 percent in October 2001 to 31 percent in 2003.<ref name=\"carlcampanile-breath\">Carl Campanile, \"9/11 is Still Taking Cops' Breath Away\", ''New York Daily News'', April 16, 2007, p. 2</ref>\n\nA 2006 medical study of fire fighters reported that those personnel who inhaled Ground Zero air essentially lost 12 years of lung function.<ref name=\"carlcampanile-breath\" /> Additionally, a Mount Sinai report found that 70 percent of recovery and rescue workers reported an increase in debilitated respiratory function between 2002 and 2004.<ref name=\"carlcampanile-breath\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://abcnews.go.com/GMA/story?id=2409716&page=1|title=9/11 First Responders Gravely Ill|author=ABC News|work=ABC News|accessdate=June 15, 2015}}</ref>\n\nA 2008 report by New York City's Department of Health indicated that up to 70,000 people might have stress disorder due to the attack. The findings were the result of the city's health registry of September 11 first responders, residents, and others.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2008/09/11/study-70000-may-suffer-po_n_125552.html |title=Study: 70,000 may suffer post-9/11 stress disorder |date=2015-11-07 |access-date=2016-11-16 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151107011239/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2008/09/11/study-70000-may-suffer-po_n_125552.html |archivedate=November 7, 2015 }}</ref>\n\n===Ground Zero-related worker's compensation===\n{{Update|date=April 2018|type=section}}\nApparently, out of at least 100,000 eligible, fewer than 14,000 have registered, as reported by the National Council for Occupational Safety and Health. The final registration deadline for September 11-related workers' compensation was August 14, 2007.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tortdeform.com/archives/2007/05/3_months_remain_for_911related.html|title=3 Months Remain for 9/11-Related Workers' Compensation Program - Tort Deform|accessdate=June 15, 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn July 12, 2007, Governor [[Eliot Spitzer]] extended to August 14, 2008, the filing deadline for [[worker's compensation]] claims, for people who worked or volunteered at Ground Zero. Individuals would register with the State Workers' Compensation Board.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/07/13/nyregion/13mbrfs-compensation.html|title=Albany: Extension for 9/11 Compensation|last=Depalma|first=Anthony|date=2007-07-13|newspaper=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=2016-11-16}}</ref> New York Governor [[Andrew Cuomo]] granted a third extension for Ground Zero rescue, recovery or clean up workers to file a notice of participation for worker' compensation benefits. This applies to workers who had not yet filled or who were denied between September 2015 and September 2017, with the new deadline being September 11, 2022.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.politico.com/states/new-york/newsletters/politico-new-york-health-care/2018/09/11/new-yorks-ground-zero-claim-limit-extended-107653|title=New York's Ground Zero claim limit extended|last=Niedzwiadek|first=Nick|last2=AM|website=Politico PRO|language=en|access-date=2019-06-04|last3=Eisenberg|first3=A.}}</ref>\n\n== Controversies ==\n\n=== President George W. Bush's alleged manipulation of EPA statements ===\n{{Main|EPA 9/11 pollution controversy}}\n\n[[File:EPA WTC 2001-10-10.jpg|thumb|An Environmental Protection Agency employee checks one of the many air sampling locations set up around the site of the World Trade Center.]]\n\nPresident [[George W. Bush]] has been faulted by the [[Sierra Club]] for allegedly interfering with the [[United States Environmental Protection Agency]] (EPA) interpretations and pronouncements regarding air quality.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sierraclub.org/groundzero/ |title=Ground Zero Report &gt; Sierra Club |format= |website= |accessdate= |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100611191219/http://www.sierraclub.org/groundzero/ |archivedate=June 11, 2010 |df= }}</ref>\n\n===Early statement by Christine Todd Whitman===\nOn September 18, 2001, [[Administrator of the Environmental Protection Agency|EPA administrator]] [[Christine Todd Whitman]] told the public, via a [[press release]], \"We are very encouraged that the results from our monitoring of air-quality and drinking-water conditions in both New York and near the Pentagon show that the public in these areas is not being exposed to excessive levels of asbestos or other harmful substances\" and that \"Given the scope of the tragedy from last week, I am glad to reassure the people of New York \u2026 that their air is safe to breathe and the water is safe to drink.\"<ref name=\"kristenlombardi\" />\n\n===Alleged EPA deceptions about Ground Zero air quality===\n{{See also|United States Environmental Protection Agency September 11 attacks pollution controversy}}\nAn August 2003 report by the Office of the Inspector General of the EPA said the Bush administration pressured the EPA to remove cautionary information about the air quality at Ground Zero.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.epa.gov/oig/reports/2003/WTC_report_20030821.pdf|title=EPA's Office of Inspector General|last=EPA,OIG|first=US|website=www.epa.gov|language=en|access-date=2016-11-16}}</ref>\n\nNumerous key differences between the draft versions and final versions of EPA statements were found. A recommendation that homes and businesses near ground zero be cleaned by professionals was replaced by a request that citizens follow orders from NYC officials. Another statement that showed concerns about \"sensitive populations\" was deleted altogether. Language used to describe excessive amounts of asbestos in the area was altered drastically to minimize the dangers it posed.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.commondreams.org/headlines03/0823-03.htm |title=EPA Misled Public on 9/11 Pollution |date=August 23, 2003 |publisher=Newsday |author=Laurie Garrett |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061120200307/http://www.commondreams.org/headlines03/0823-03.htm |archivedate=November 20, 2006 |df= }}</ref>\n\nIn September 2006, the [[United States House Committee on Homeland Security|U.S. House Committee on Homeland Security]] held a two-day hearing on illnesses caused by post-9/11 air quality. Former EPA head Christine Todd Whitman was a frequent target of criticism.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/home/feeds/ap/2006/09/08/ap3004093.html|title=EPA, NYC Blamed for 9/11 Health Problems|date=September 8, 2006|publisher=Associated Press|author=Devlin Barrett}}</ref>\n\nEPA scientist Dr. Cate Jenkins said on [[CBS]] television on September 8, 2006, that agency officials lied about the air quality in the weeks following September 11, 2001. She said that in her opinion the EPA knew about the toxicity of the air, and that WTC dust included asbestos and disturbingly high PH levels. She said that some of the dust was \"as caustic and alkaline as [[Drano]].\"<ref name=\"cbsnews1985804\">{{cite news|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2006/09/08/earlyshow/main1985804.shtml|title=Insider: EPA Lied About WTC Air|date=September 8, 2006|work=CBS News}}</ref> [[Marjorie Clarke|Dr. Marjorie Clarke]] also warned of the consequences of breathing toxic dust and fumes. Yet, agencies did not heed her warnings.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://wtceo.org/|title=World Trade Center Environmental Organization|accessdate=June 15, 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe [[New York State Department of Environmental Conservation]] conducted a study of the World Trade Center site, but refused to release the results of its study, saying they were part of a criminal investigation.<ref>Juan Gonzalez, \"Fallout: The Hidden Consequences of 9/11\", ''In These Times'', September 10, 2002 http://www.alternet.org/911oneyearlater/14073/</ref>\n\nOn September 13, 2006, Congressmen [[Jerrold Nadler]] (NY), [[Anthony Weiner]] (NY), [[Bill Pascrell]] Jr. (NJ) filed a request with [[US Attorney General]] [[Alberto Gonzales]] to investigate whether criminal charges may be brought against Whitman for lying about air safety in the Ground Zero area.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.house.gov/list/press/ny08_nadler/WhitmanProsecuted091306.html |title=Press Release of Representative Jerrold Nadler |date=2012-07-15 |access-date=2016-11-16 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120715030049/http://www.house.gov/list/press/ny08_nadler/WhitmanProsecuted091306.html |archivedate=July 15, 2012 }}</ref>\n\n===Alleged government downplaying of health risks===\nCritics assert that government officials \u2013 notably Bush, Christine Todd Whitman (former head of the US EPA), and New York City mayor [[Rudy Giuliani]] \u2013 downplayed the health risks of the area and rushed to reopen the area around Ground Zero, although this posed a grave and immediate health risk to first responders.<ref>Persons interviewed in ''Dust to Dust:The Health Effects of 9/11.''</ref> Many corporations were eager to hear the news of the [[New York Stock Exchange]] being reopened only a few days after the collapse.<ref name=\"autogenerated2\">Juan Gonzalez, \"Former head of EPA Whitman doesn't second guess opening up lower Manhattan after 9/11\", ''New York Daily News'', June 26, 2007, p. 5</ref> On June 25, 2007, Whitman testified before a [[United States House of Representatives|House of Representatives]] committee chaired by [[Jerrold Nadler]]. She said that a [[White House]] official informed her that President Bush expected that the Financial District would reopen within three days, that is, by September 14. She said that she replied that this would be cumbersome, since the EPA was still judging the health situation in the area.<ref name=\"autogenerated2\" />\nInvestigations after the attacks suggest that the Bush administration pressured Whitman and Giuliani to provide health reassurances in order to keep Wall Street operating.<ref name=\"andrewstephen\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.newstatesman.com/world-affairs/2007/06/york-air-death-city-breathe|title=The poisonous legacy of 9/11|website=www.newstatesman.com|access-date=2016-11-16}}</ref><ref name=\"bensmith\">Ben Smith, Rudy's Black Cloud: WTC Health Risks May Hurt Prez Bid.\" ''New York Daily News'', September 18, 2006, p. 14</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.villagevoice.com/news/rudy-giulianis-five-big-lies-about-9-11-6424659|title=Rudy Giuliani's Five Big Lies About 9/11|last=Kahan|first=Wayne Barrett with special research assistance by Alexandra|date=2007-07-31|newspaper=Village Voice|access-date=2016-11-16}}</ref>\n\nTwo days after the [[collapse of the World Trade Center]], mayor Giuliani said, \"The air is safe as far as we can tell, with respect to chemical and biological agents.\"<ref name=\"michaelmason\">{{Cite news|url=http://discovermagazine.com/2007/oct/the-9-11-cover-up|title=The 9/11 Cover-Up {{!}} DiscoverMagazine.com|newspaper=Discover Magazine|access-date=2016-11-16}}</ref> Giuliani, in attempting to deflate ''[[New York Daily News]]'' journalist [[Juan Gonzalez (journalist)|Juan Gonzalez]]' reportage of the 9/11 air issue, claimed that \"the problems created\u2026 are not health-threatening.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.villagevoice.com/nyclife/0717%2Chagey%2C76442%2C15.html |title=village voice > nyclife > Press Clips: Dishonorable Non-Mention: Juan Gonzalez and the Daily News' 9/11 Pulitzer by Keach Hagey |date=2008-02-13 |access-date=2016-11-16 |url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080213050647/http://www.villagevoice.com/nyclife/0717%2Chagey%2C76442%2C15.html |archivedate=February 13, 2008 }}</ref>\nIn the first month after the attacks, the mayor said, \"The air quality is safe and acceptable.\"<ref name=\"anitagates\" />\n\nIn November 2001, Giuliani wrote to the city's Congressional delegation and urged that the city's [[legal liability|liability]] for Ground Zero illnesses be limited, in total, at $350 million. Two years after Mayor Giuliani finished his term, FEMA appropriated $1 billion to a special insurance fund to protect the city against 9/11 lawsuits.<ref name=\"anthonydepalma\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/05/14/nyregion/14giuliani.html|title=Ground Zero Illnesses Clouding Giuliani's Legacy|last=Depalma|first=Anthony|date=2007-05-14|newspaper=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=2016-11-16}}</ref>\n\nIn a September 18, 2006 ''New York Daily News'' article titled, \"Rudy's Black Cloud: WTC health risks may hurt Prez Bid\", [[Sally Regenhard]], mother of firefighter Christian Regenhard who died on September 11, is quoted, \"There's a large and growing number of both FDNY families, FDNY members, former and current, and civilian families who want to expose the true failures of the Giuliani administration when it comes to 9/11.\" She told the ''New York Daily News'' that she intends to \"[[Swiftboating|Swift Boat]]\" Giuliani.<ref name=\"bensmith\" />\n\nThen senator [[Hillary Clinton]] contemplated calling Giuliani to testify before a Senate committee on whether the government failed to protect recovery workers from the effects of polluted Ground Zero air.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.latimes.com/news/nationworld/nation/la-na-giuliani8apr08,0,2321840,print.story?coll=la-home-headlines |title=Giuliani foes plan to use 9/11 against him |last=Wallsten |first=Peter |date=April 8, 2007 |work=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=May 4, 2010 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070621112054/http://www.latimes.com/news/nationworld/nation/la-na-giuliani8apr08%2C0%2C2321840%2Cprint.story?coll=la-home-headlines |archivedate=June 21, 2007 |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nysun.com/article/49582|title=Potential Clinton-Giuliani Battle Brews Over 9/11 Health Issues|accessdate=June 15, 2015}}</ref>\n\nCongressman Nadler was quoted in a March 1, 2007, \"New York Sun\" article, \"Potential Clinton-Giuliani Battle Brews Over 9/11 Health Issues.\" He said that he \"absolutely\" wishes to interview Giuliani administration officials regarding the environment in the aftermath of the September 11 attacks. He asked, \"Who made decisions, if any, that resulted unnecessarily in a lot of people getting sick?\"<ref>Russell Berman, \"Potential Clinton-Giuliani Battle Brews Over 9/11 Health Issues\", ''New York Sun', March 1, 2007''</ref>\n\n===Handling of cleanup procedure===\nA May 14, 2007, ''New York Times'' article, \"Ground Zero Illness Clouding Giuliani's Legacy\", gave the interpretation that thousands of workers at Ground Zero have become sick and that \"many regard Mr. Giuliani's triumph of leadership as having come with a human cost.\" The article reported that he seized control of the cleanup of Ground Zero, taking control away from established federal agencies, such as the [[Federal Emergency Management Agency]], the [[United States Army Corps of Engineers|Army Corps of Engineers]] and the [[Occupational Safety and Health Administration]]. He instead handed over responsibility to the \"largely unknown\" city Department of Design and Construction. Documents indicate that the Giuliani administration never enforced federal requirements requiring the wearing of [[respirators]]. Concurrently, the administration threatened companies with dismissal if cleanup work slowed.<ref name=\"anthonydepalma\" />\n\nWorkers worked without proper respirators. They wore painters' masks or no covering. Specialists claim that the only effective protection against toxins such as airborne asbestos, is a special respirator. New York Committee for Occupational Safety and Health industrial hygienist David Newman said, \"I was down there watching people working without respirators.\" He continued, \"Others took off their respirators to eat. It was a surreal, ridiculous, unacceptable situation.\"<ref name=\"michaelmason\" />\n\nThe local EPA office sidelined the regional EPA office. Dr. Cate Jenkins, a whistle-blower EPA scientist, said that on September 12, 2001, a regional EPA office offered to dispatch 30 to 40 electron microscopes to the WTC pit to test bulk dust samples for the presence of asbestos fibers. Instead, the local office chose the less effective polarized light microscopy testing method. Dr. Jenkins alleged that the local office refused, saying, \"We don't want you f\u2014ing cowboys here. The best thing they could do is reassign you to Alaska.\"<ref name=\"michaelmason\" />\n\n===Lawsuit, settlement, and treatment costs===\nFirst responders and other individuals are suing the City of New York. Lawyers are criticizing the city for failing to provide proper facial [[ventilators]] to [[Rescue and recovery effort after the September 11, 2001 attacks|clean-up workers]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/06/23/nyregion/23responders.html|title=9/11 Suit Tests New York Stand on Immunity|last=Depalma|first=Anthony|date=2006-06-23|newspaper=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=2016-11-16}}</ref>\nOn October 17, 2006, federal judge [[Alvin K. Hellerstein]] rejected New York City's motion to dismiss lawsuits that requested health payments to the first responders.<ref>Anthony DePalma, \"Ruling Opens a Door for Thousands of Ground Zero Lawsuits\", ''The New York Times'', October 18, 2006, B1.</ref>\n\nOn November 19, 2010, attorneys said that plaintiffs accepted a settlement which should lead to $625 million being paid to more than 10,000 workers experiencing problems as a result of inadequate preparation to work at Ground Zero. Not all affected participated, but those who did not would be eligible for a portion of $7.4 billion provided by the [[James Zadroga 9/11 Health and Compensation Act]], which the [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. House]] passed in September 2010. New York City Mayor [[Michael Bloomberg]] asked the [[United States Senate|Senate]] to do the same. The plaintiffs in the settlement would also be eligible for compensation under the Zadroga Act.<ref name=\"Solomon\">{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2010/US/11/19/ny.911.workers.settlement/index.html|title=9/11 workers approve settlement with New York City|last=Solomon|first=Jesse|date=November 19, 2010|work=[[CNN]]|accessdate=2010-11-23}}</ref>\n\nOn December 22, 2010, the [[United States Senate]] passed a 9/11 Health Bill running against opposition of the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]] and aided by advocacy from comedian [[Jon Stewart]].<ref name=\"Stewart NYT\">{{cite news |last1=Gold |first1=Michael |title=How Jon Stewart Became a Fierce Advocate for 9/11 Responders |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/06/12/nyregion/jon-stewart-9-11-congress.html |accessdate=12 June 2019 |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=June 12, 2019}}</ref> The measure calls for providing $1.8 billion until 2015 to monitor and treat injuries stemming from exposure to toxic dust and debris at [[World Trade Center site]]. There are nearly 60,000 people enrolled in health-monitoring and treatment programs related to the 9/11 attack. The bill is formally known as the [[James Zadroga]] 9/11 Health and Compensation Act, named after a New York police detective who took part in the rescue efforts at ground zero and later developed breathing complications.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/12/23/nyregion/23health.html?nl=todaysheadlines&emc=a2|title=Senate Passes 9/11 Health Bill as Republicans Back Down|last=Hernandez|first=Raymond|date=December 22, 2010|work=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=2010-12-23}}</ref>\n\nOn October 28, 2007, Jim Riches reported that the City of New York and litigating first responders have shown interest in a [[legal settlement]], to resolve lawsuits against the city. The settlement would yield a financial settlement apportioned in the following manner: forty percent to lawyers, and sixty percent to litigants.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.freemarketnews.com/WorldNews.asp?nid=50810 |title=Ducking WTC Air Blame? - Free Market News Network |date=2007-10-29 |access-date=2016-11-16 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071029111031/http://www.freemarketnews.com/WorldNews.asp?nid=50810 |archivedate=October 29, 2007 }}</ref>\n\nThe [[National Institute for Occupational Safety and Health]] issued a study on July 17, 2007, indicating that the estimates for monthly costs of treating Ground Zero workers had increased from around $6 million per month to $20 million per month by the end of 2007. The causes of the increased expense lie in the increasing numbers of workers getting sick and the worsening illnesses of workers. This indicated that the planned U.S. House appropriation legislation (of $50 million) for the sick workers, for the coming year, would be inadequate. The number of workers that have registered with area hospitals' Ground Zero programs has reached 37,000. With about 500 new workers registering each month, the institute estimated that the number of registrants could reach 65,000 in two years. (The institute is overseen by the [[Department of Health and Human Services]].)<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/07/18/nyregion/18treatment.html|title=Big Cost Increase Is Predicted to Treat Ground Zero Workers|last=Depalma|first=Anthony|date=2007-07-18|newspaper=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=2016-11-16}}</ref> 40 percent of the World Trade Center workers being monitored by a Mount Sinai Hospital study lack health insurance.<ref name=\"cbsnews1985804\" />\n\nIn June 2008, New York City argued in federal court that 30 percent of the September 11 plaintiffs did not have serious injuries.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/06/25/nyregion/25health.html|title=City Questions 9/11 Workers' Claims of Illness|last=Depalma|first=Anthony|date=2008-06-25|newspaper=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=2016-11-16}}</ref> This is part of a larger debate over the number of people sickened by the collapse of the Twin Towers.{{Citation needed|date=July 2008}}\n\n===World Trade Center health administrators===\nOn June 11, 2007, Mayor Bloomberg appointed Jeffrey Hon as World Trade Center health coordinator. Hon had previously worked as the spokesman for the [[American Red Cross]] September 11 Recovery Program. People have offered conflicting statements, however, regarding Hon's role. In an interview with the ''[[New York Daily News]]'' Hon said that his role was to correct inconsistencies in city agencies and to handle related pension issues. Yet, Mayor Bloomberg said that Hon's role would not involve handling pension-related issues. A press release also indicated that the coordinator will \"provide a central repository of WTC health information and ensure effective communication with those who may be experiencing 9/11-related health effects.\"<ref>Jordan Lite and Michael Saul, ''Daily News'', June 12, 2007, p. 4</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://media-newswire.com/release_1052193.html|title=Media-Newswire.com - Press Release Distribution - PR Agency|last=Distribution|first=Media-Newswire.com - Press Release|website=media-newswire.com|access-date=2016-11-16}}</ref>\n\nDr. [[John Howard (public health administrator)|John Howard]] was appointed the medical administrator of the federal [[World Trade Center Health Program]] funded through the [[Zadroga Act|James Zadroga Act]]. On July 22, 2011, Howard's report on a study of a link between particulate exposure in the aftermath and cancer was released. The report said that there was insufficient evidence of a link between particulate exposure and cancer. The report's findings meant that many first responders to the attacks would be limited in their access to funds for medical treatment. Three New York Congressional delegation Representatives, [[Peter T. King]], [[Carolyn B. Maloney]] and [[Jerrold Nadler]], said that they believed that further studies would indicate a link between exposures and cancer.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/07/27/nyregion/not-enough-evidence-to-link-911-and-cancer-report-finds.html|title=Not Enough Evidence to Link 9/11 and Cancer, Report Finds|last=Hartocollis|first=Anemona|date=2011-07-26|newspaper=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=2016-11-16}}</ref>\n\n=== Lawsuit by area residents ===\nLower Manhattan and [[Brooklyn]] residents brought a 111-page lawsuit against the EPA for purported deception of the public about hazards of Ground Zero air and dust. A major force behind this effort is Brooklyn resident Jenna Orkin of the World Trade Center Environmental Organization. On February 2, 2006, Federal Court Judge [[Deborah Batts]] issued an 83-page statement, indicating that there are sufficient grounds for the case to proceed. She also rejected granting Whitman immunity from the lawsuit.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.villagevoice.com/news/truth-out-6399648|title=Truth Out|last=Lombardi|first=Kristen|date=2006-02-14|newspaper=Village Voice|access-date=2016-11-16}}</ref>\n\nOn December 10, 2007, legal proceedings began in a case on the question of responsibility of government officials in the aftermath of the September 11, 2001, attacks. Former EPA Director Whitman is among the defendants in the suit; plaintiffs in the suit allege that Whitman is at fault for saying that the downtown Manhattan air was safe in the aftermath of the attacks.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/news/2007/12/11/2007-12-11_christie_whitman_lied_about_ground_zero_.html|title=Christie lied, panel is told|newspaper=NY Daily News|access-date=2016-11-16}}</ref>\n\nOn April 22, 2008, the [[United States Court of Appeals for the Second Circuit]] ruled that EPA head Whitman could not be held liable for saying to World Trade Center area residents that the air was safe for breathing after the buildings collapse. The appeals court said that Whitman had based her information on contradictory information and statements from President Bush. The [[United States Department of Justice|U.S. Department of Justice]] had argued that holding the agency liable would establish a risky [[legal precedent]] because future public officials would be afraid to make public statements. Judge [[Deborah Batts]] had previously declined to dismiss Whitman as a defendant, saying that her actions were \"conscience-shocking\".<ref>The [[Associated Press]] April 22, 2008, https://www.nytimes.com/aponline/us/AP-EPA-Sept-11-Lawsuit.html?_r=1&scp=2&sq=whitman&st=nyt&oref=slogin</ref>\n\nAn arbitrator has said that most of the complainants that did not participate in an earlier fund (created by Congress) would be granted settlement awards. The awards would total $500 million. This resolution would involve all but 3 of the nearly 100 litigants.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ny1.com/content/news_beats/politics/95030/most-september-11th-lawsuits-settled-for--500-million/ |title=Most September 11th Lawsuits Settled For $500 Million - NY1.com |date=2012-08-20 |access-date=2016-11-16 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120820010051/http://www.ny1.com/content/news_beats/politics/95030/most-september-11th-lawsuits-settled-for--500-million/ |archivedate=August 20, 2012 }}</ref>\n\n=== Ground Zero workers' and area residents' protests ===\nOn January 30, 2007, Ground Zero workers and groups such as [[Sierra Club]] and Unsung Heroes Helping Heroes met at the Ground Zero site and urged President [[George W. Bush]] to spend more money on aid for sick Ground Zero workers. They said that the $25 million that Bush promised for the ill workers was inadequate. A Long Island iron-worker, John Sferazo, at the protest rally said, \"Why has it taken you 5\u00bd years to meet with us, Mr. President?\"<ref name=\"emiendo\" />\n\nArea residents joined the protest. Mariama James, who lives within blocks of the Ground Zero site, said that she became ill after cleaning the Ground Zero debris and dust from her apartment. \"Recovery workers aren't the only people that were affected by this disaster,\" she said. \"There are other people in need of treatment and monitoring.\"<ref name=\"emiendo\" />\n\n===Ground Zero workers' lawsuit===\nFamilies of Ground Zero workers have filed a mass lawsuit against the city. Andrew Carboy of the firm, Sulivan, Pappain, Block, McGrath and Cannovo said of the deaths of Cesar Borja, James Zadroga, and Mark DeBiase, \"If Borja, Zadroga and now DeBiase isn't a wakeup call for the city, I don't know what will wake them.\"<ref name=\"carlcampanile-kinsuing\" />\n\nBy June 2007, the number of people filing claims against the city, regarding exposure to Ground Zero toxins, reached 10,000.<ref name=\"andrewstephen\" /> Attorney [[David Worby]] is leading a [[class action]] lawsuit representing 8,000 people.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://maloney.house.gov/index.php?option=content&task=view&id=1232&Itemid=61|title=Congresswoman Carolyn Maloney|accessdate=June 15, 2015}}</ref> By September 2007, the number of [[plaintiff]]s in the case reached 10,000. \"I started this suit on behalf of one cop that got sick.\" He continued, \"Nobody would touch the case with a 10-foot pole because it was considered unpatriotic to say anything against the cleanup or the [[United States Environmental Protection Agency|EPA]].<ref name=\"michaelmason\"/>\n\n==Vulnerable individuals==\n\nIn 2008, the lead researcher of a [[New York State Department of Health]] study informed ''[[The New York Post]]'' of a study documenting at least 204 deaths of rescue and recovery workers since September 11, 2001. The researchers for the study confirmed 98 deaths with death certificates. The researchers showed that 77 persons died of illnesses, including 55 from lung and various other cancers. Kitty Gelberg, New York state Bureau of Occupational Health's chief epidemiologist said, \"We're not saying they are all World Trade Center related; we're just saying this is what people are dying from.\" Many of the 55 responders who died from cancer had cancer before September 11, 2001, but most of the cancer patients developed the disease afterward.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">Susan Edelman, \"Charting post-9/11 deaths\", ''New York Post'', January 6, 2008, p. 2</ref>\n\nThe 98 deaths up to 2008 included:\n*55 cancers\n*21 traumatic injuries (motor-vehicle crashes, gunshots and five homicides, including four cops killed in the line of duty)\n*12 heart disease, including 10 heart attacks\n*2 [[sarcoidosis]]\n*1 [[polyneuropathy]] (neorological disorder)\n*1 pneumonia\n*1 [[pneumonitis|granuloma pneumonitis]]\n*1 alcoholism\n*1 [[amyloidosis]] ([[bone marrow]] disorder)\n*1 kidney disease<ref name=\"autogenerated1\" />\n\n===First responders===\n{{expand section | additional information about circumstances of each responder's death|date=November 2016}}{{See also|Rescue and recovery effort after the September 11 attacks on the World Trade Center}}\n\nIn particular, ''first responders,'' New York Police Department and Fire Department of New York members that reported to Ground Zero, have asserted that they are victims of diseases associated with the toxic cloud from the pulverized buildings and equipment.\nNYPD Detective [[James Zadroga]], 34, was the first 9/11 responder whose 2006 death was directly linked with toxic Ground Zero substances.<ref name=\"twfarnam\" />\nGerard Breton, a pathologist of the [[Ocean County, New Jersey]] medical examiner's office (which conducted an [[autopsy]]), reported that \"It is felt with a reasonable degree of medical certainty that the cause of death in this case was directly related to the 9/11 incident.\"<ref name=\"richschapiro\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_qn4155/is_20060421/ai_n16153072 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2006-11-18 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151107011256/http://www.findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_qn4155/is_20060421/ai_n16153072 |archivedate=November 7, 2015 |df= }} or Devlin Barrett, \"Ground Zero workers seek answers: Autopsy links cop's death to dust\", ''Chicago Sun-Times'', April 21, 2006.</ref> In addition to ''first responders'' that responded to the initial attack on the World Trade Center many assisted during recovery operations.\n\nIn 2017, 24 members of the NYPD died of cancer linked to toxins from the terrorist attack. In the first five months of 2018, another 24 members of the NYPD died of the same cause.<ref name=\"New York Daily News\">{{cite news|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/new-york/nypd-chief-william-allee-dies-9-11-linked-leukemia-article-1.4007814|title=Former NYPD chief, William Allee, dies of 9/11-linked leukemia|last1=Parascandola|first1=Rocco|date=24 May 2018|accessdate=24 May 2018|publisher=New York Daily News}}</ref>\n\n==== Examples of health issues ====\nCesar Borja, a veteran of the NYPD, died, falling ill from lung disease. He had spent 16-hour days at the smoldering wreckage of Ground Zero.<ref>ADAM LISBERG, NICOLE BODE and DAVID SALTONSTALL, \"Look me in the eye\n& save WTC heroes\" New York Daily News January 25, 2007 http://www.nydailynews.com/news/local/story/491657p-414162c.html</ref> Detective Robert Williamson, 46, died from pancreatic and lung cancer on May 13, 2007. He worked for 16-hour days, without taking days off, in performing recovery work at the Ground Zero site. After the clean up effort, he was among individuals that lobbied Governor George Pataki to sign a bill permitting retirees suffering from Ground Zero illnesses to have their illnesses reclassified and to receive additional pension benefits. His family and union believe that his cancers were directly caused by exposure to Ground Zero dust at the World Trade Center site.<ref>Reuven Blau, \"'Hero Times 2' Detective A Cancer Victim\", ''[[The Chief-Leader|The Chief]]'', May 25, 2007, p. 1</ref><ref>SARAH NETTER, \"Nanuet man dies at 46; Ground Zero-link suspected\", ''The Journal News'', May 15, 2007, http://www.thejournalnews.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20070515/NEWS03/705150364/1019/NEWS03 {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927204506/http://www.thejournalnews.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=%2F20070515%2FNEWS03%2F705150364%2F1019%2FNEWS03 |date=September 27, 2007 }}</ref> Twenty year veteran of the NYPD, Officer Kevin Hawkins, 41, died in May 2007 from kidney cancer, soon after filing for a Ground Zero disability pension. He had worked two months at the Ground Zero site.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.earthtimes.org/articles/show/60706.html|title=Earth Times: show/60706.html|accessdate=June 15, 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn September 3, 2007, NYPD Officer Frank Macri died of lung cancer that spread throughout his body, including to his spine.<ref name=\"nydailynews.com22\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/life-style/health/ray-hope-fight-cancer-article-1.251701|title=Cop's ray of hope in fight with cancer|newspaper=NY Daily News|access-date=2016-11-16}}</ref> Macri's lungs were filled with dust when the towers collapsed and he later spent two months working on the site. The long hours on the site gave him vomiting spells and he was diagnosed with an already rapidly progressing stage four cancer only one year after the attack, despite being a non-smoker and cancer free before the attacks.<ref name=\"nydailynews.com\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/news/2007/09/10/2007-09-10_cancer_ends_his_fitness_life_after_toil_.html|title=Cancer ends his fitness life after toil at the Pit|newspaper=NY Daily News|access-date=2016-11-16}}</ref> In 2011, a lower court ruled that 9/11 toxins were the likely cause of Macri's death.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/news/national/widow-nypd-lucrative-benefits-city-failed-prove-lung-cancer-caused-world-trade-center-toxins-court-article-1.997405|title=Court: 9/11 toxins likely caused cop's fatal cancer|newspaper=NY Daily News|access-date=2016-11-16}}</ref> In 2012, the [[New York Supreme Court]] ruled that Macri's widow is entitled to line-of-duty death benefits of his full salary.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nypost.com/2012/12/13/ny-top-court-extends-911-benefits-for-3-police-officers/|title=NY top court extends 9/11 benefits for 3 police officers|last=Report|first=Post Staff|date=2012-12-13|website=New York Post|access-date=2016-11-16}}</ref> On December 12, 2017, NYPD Captain Douglas Greenwood took his own life after a long battle with lung disease, brought on by deadly chemicals in the air while working alongside other officers at Ground Zero. The pain he suffered over the years became too much to manage, causing him to take his own life by shooting himself in the chest near his home in Suffolk County, New York.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-5178447/NYPD-9-11-hero-kills-lung-disease-battle.html|title=NYPD 9/11 hero kills himself after long painful lung disease battle|first=Tariq|last=Tahir|date=December 14, 2017|website=Mail Online}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lifeandstylemag.com/posts/911-first-responder-suicide-lung-disease-149182|title=9/11 First Responder Douglas Greenwood Commits Suicide After Battling Lung Disease|date=December 15, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===== General list of deceased due to health effects =====\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+\n!Name\n!Rank or Role\n!Organisation\n!Date of Death\n! class=\"unsortable\" |\n|-\n|Felicia Dunn-Jones\n|Attorney\n|\n|February 10 2002\n|<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/05/24/nyregion/24dust.html|title=For the First Time, New York Links a Death to 9/11 Dust|last=|first=|date=May 24, 2007|work=The New York Times|access-date=July 8, 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n|Thomas F. Weiner Jr.\n|Detective\n|New York City Police Department\n|May 3 2003\n|<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.odmp.org/officer/22342-detective-thomas-f-weiner-jr|title=Detective Thomas F. Weiner, Jr.|newspaper=The Officer Down Memorial Page (ODMP)|access-date=2016-11-29}}</ref>\n|-\n|William B. Titus Jr.\n|Detective\n|New York City Police Department\n|August 24 2003\n|<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.odmp.org/officer/22482-detective-william-b-titus-jr|title=Detective William B. Titus, Jr.|newspaper=The Officer Down Memorial Page (ODMP)|access-date=2016-11-29}}</ref>\n|-\n|Edward M. Ferraro\n|Officer\n|New York City Police Department\n|June 6 2004\n|<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.odmp.org/officer/21237-police-officer-edward-m-ferraro|title=Police Officer Edward M. Ferraro|newspaper=The Officer Down Memorial Page (ODMP)|access-date=2016-11-16}}</ref>\n|-\n|James J. Godbee\n|Officer\n|New York City Police Department\n|December 30 2004\n|<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.odmp.org/officer/19087-police-officer-james-j-godbee|title=Police Officer James J. Godbee|newspaper=The Officer Down Memorial Page (ODMP)|access-date=2016-11-16}}</ref>\n|-\n|Thomas G. Brophy\n|Officer\n|New York City Police Department\n|April 21 2005\n|<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.odmp.org/officer/19088-police-officer-thomas-g-brophy|title=Police Officer Thomas G. Brophy|newspaper=The Officer Down Memorial Page (ODMP)|access-date=2016-11-16}}</ref>\n|-\n|Ronald E. Weintraub\n|Officer\n|New York City Police Department\n|November 16 2005\n|<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.odmp.org/officer/19086-police-officer-ronald-e-weintraub|title=Police Officer Ronald E. Weintraub|newspaper=The Officer Down Memorial Page (ODMP)|access-date=2016-11-29}}</ref>\n|-\n|James Zadroga\n|Detective\n|New York City Police Department\n|January 5 2006\n|<ref>\"City says drug use, not dust killed 9/11 hero James Zadroga. \"[[New York Daily News]]\" http://www.nydailynews.com/news/2007/10/26/2007-10-26_city_says_drug_use_not_dust_killed_911_h-2.html</ref>\n|-\n|Sandra Y. Adrian\n|Detective\n|New York City Police Department\n|January 11 2006\n|<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.odmp.org/officer/19954-detective-sandra-y-adrian|title=Detective Sandra Y. Adrian|newspaper=The Officer Down Memorial Page (ODMP)|access-date=2016-11-16}}</ref>\n|-\n|Edward C. Gilpin\n|Captain\n|New York City Police Department\n|September 7 2006\n|<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.odmp.org/officer/19955-captain-edward-c-gilpin|title=Captain Edward C. Gilpin|newspaper=The Officer Down Memorial Page (ODMP)|access-date=2016-11-16}}</ref>\n|-\n|Daniel C. Conroy\n|Officer\n|New York City Police Department\n|December 3 2006\n|<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.odmp.org/officer/20273-police-officer-daniel-c-conroy|title=Police Officer Daniel C. Conroy|newspaper=The Officer Down Memorial Page (ODMP)|access-date=2016-11-16}}</ref>\n|-\n|Cesar Borja\n|Officer\n|New York City Police Department\n|January 23 2007\n|<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.odmp.org/officer/19093-police-officer-cesar-a-borja|title=Police Officer Cesar A. Borja|newspaper=The Officer Down Memorial Page (ODMP)|access-date=2016-11-16}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/02/13/nyregion/13health.html|title=Weeks After a Death, Twists in Some 9/11 Details|last=Chan|first=Sewell|date=2007-02-13|newspaper=The New York Times|access-date=2016-11-16|last2=Baker|first2=Al|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n|-\n|Louise M. Johnston\n|Officer\n|New York City Police Department\n|March 6 2007\n|<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.odmp.org/officer/20274-police-officer-louise-m-johnston|title=Police Officer Louise M. Johnston|newspaper=The Officer Down Memorial Page (ODMP)|access-date=2016-11-16}}</ref>\n|-\n|Kevin Hawkins\n|Detective\n|New York City Police Department\n|May 7 2007\n|<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.odmp.org/officer/19117-detective-kevin-hawkins|title=Detective Kevin Hawkins|newspaper=The Officer Down Memorial Page (ODMP)|access-date=2016-11-16}}</ref>\n|-\n|Robert Williamson\n|Detective\n|New York City Police Department\n|May 13 2007\n|<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.odmp.org/officer/19094-detective-robert-w-williamson|title=Detective Robert W. Williamson|last=|first=|date=|website=Officer Down Memorial Page|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=July 8, 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n|Madeline Carlo\n|Officer\n|New York City Police Department\n|July 15 2007\n|<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.odmp.org/officer/19095-police-officer-madeline-carlo|title=Police Officer Madeline Carlo|newspaper=The Officer Down Memorial Page (ODMP)|access-date=2016-11-16}}</ref>\n|-\n|Robert B. Helmke\n|Officer\n|New York City Police Department\n|July 28 2007\n|<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.odmp.org/officer/19959-police-officer-robert-b-helmke|title=Police Officer Robert B. Helmke|newspaper=The Officer Down Memorial Page (ODMP)|access-date=2016-11-16}}</ref>\n|-\n|Claire T. Hanrahan\n|Sergeant\n|New York City Police Department\n|August 28 2007\n|<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.odmp.org/officer/19960-sergeant-claire-t-hanrahan|title=Sergeant Claire T. Hanrahan|newspaper=The Officer Down Memorial Page (ODMP)|access-date=2016-11-16}}</ref>\n|-\n|Frank Macri\n|Officer\n|New York City Police Department\n|September 3 2007\n|<ref name=\"auto22\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.odmp.org/officer/19455-police-officer-frank-macri|title=Police Officer Frank Macri|newspaper=The Officer Down Memorial Page (ODMP)|access-date=2016-11-16}}</ref><ref name=\"nydailynews.com22\" /><ref name=\"Another of the Forgotten Victims22\">{{Cite web|url=http://nycpba.org/publications/mag-08-12/macri.html|title=Another of the Forgotten Victims|date=2009-01-31|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090131115921/http://nycpba.org/publications/mag-08-12/macri.html|archivedate=January 31, 2009|access-date=2016-11-16|url-status=dead|df=}}</ref>\n|-\n|William J. Holfester\n|Detective\n|New York City Police Department\n|January 22 2008\n|<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.odmp.org/officer/19958-detective-william-j-holfester|title=Detective William J. Holfester|newspaper=The Officer Down Memorial Page (ODMP)|access-date=2016-11-16}}</ref>\n|-\n|John E. Goggin\n|Detective\n|New York City Police Department\n|May 6 2008\n|<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.odmp.org/officer/21238-detective-john-e-goggin|title=Detective John E. Goggin|newspaper=The Officer Down Memorial Page (ODMP)|access-date=2016-11-16}}</ref>\n|-\n|Gary Mausberg\n|Officer\n|New York City Police Department\n|October 8 2008\n|<ref>{{