ano|newspaper=The Officer Down Memorial Page (ODMP)|access-date=2016-11-16}}</ref>\n|-\n|Karen E. Barnes\n|Officer\n|New York City Police Department\n|August 4 2011\n|<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.odmp.org/officer/22330-police-officer-karen-e-barnes|title=Police Officer Karen E. Barnes|newspaper=The Officer Down Memorial Page (ODMP)|access-date=2016-11-16}}</ref>\n|-\n|Charles D. Cole Jr.\n|Officer\n|Nassau County Police Department\n|August 14 2011\n|<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.odmp.org/officer/21255-police-officer-charles-d-cole-jr|title=Police Officer Charles D. Cole, Jr.|newspaper=The Officer Down Memorial Page (ODMP)|access-date=2016-11-16}}</ref>\n|-\n|Alick W. Herrmann\n|Detective\n|New York City Police Department\n|December 23 2011\n|<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.odmp.org/officer/21902-detective-alick-w-herrmann|title=Detective Alick W. Herrmann|newspaper=The Officer Down Memorial Page (ODMP)|access-date=2016-11-16}}</ref>\n|-\n|Richard G. Holland\n|Officer\n|New York City Police Department\n|March 23 2012\n|<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.odmp.org/officer/22328-police-officer-richard-g-holland|title=Police Officer Richard G. Holland|newspaper=The Officer Down Memorial Page (ODMP)|access-date=2016-11-16}}</ref>\n|-\n|Garrett Danza\n|Sergeant\n|New York City Police Department\n|July 11 2012\n|<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.odmp.org/officer/21904-sergeant-garrett-danza|title=Sergeant Garrett Danza|newspaper=The Officer Down Memorial Page (ODMP)|access-date=2016-11-16}}</ref>\n|-\n|Ronald G. Becker Jr.\n|Officer\n|New York City Police Department\n|August 19 2012\n|<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.odmp.org/officer/22329-police-officer-ronald-g-becker-jr|title=Police Officer Ronald G. Becker, Jr.|newspaper=The Officer Down Memorial Page (ODMP)|access-date=2016-11-16}}</ref>\n|-\n|John F. Kristoffersen\n|Detective\n|New York City Police Department\n|August 25 2012\n|<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.odmp.org/officer/22343-detective-john-f-kristoffersen|title=Detective John F. Kristoffersen|newspaper=The Officer Down Memorial Page (ODMP)|access-date=2016-11-16}}</ref>\n|-\n|Steven L. Cioffi\n|Lieutenant\n|New York City Police Department\n|March 5 2013\n|<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.odmp.org/officer/22345-lieutenant-steven-l-cioffi|title=Lieutenant Steven L. Cioffi|newspaper=The Officer Down Memorial Page (ODMP)|access-date=2016-11-16}}</ref>\n|-\n|Carmen M. Figueroa\n|Detective\n|New York City Police Department\n|May 26 2013\n|<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.odmp.org/officer/22346-detective-carmen-m-figueroa|title=Detective Carmen M. Figueroa|newspaper=The Officer Down Memorial Page (ODMP)|access-date=2016-11-16}}</ref>\n|-\n|Steven Bonano\n|Deputy Chief\n|New York City Police Department\n|January 17 2015\n|<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.odmp.org/officer/22341-deputy-chief-steven-bonano|title=Deputy Chief Steven Bonano|newspaper=The Officer Down Memorial Page (ODMP)|access-date=2016-11-16}}</ref>\n|-\n|William Sheldon\n|Special Agent\n|Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms\n|March 2 2015\n|<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.odmp.org/officer/22402-special-agent-william-sheldon|title=Special Agent William C. Sheldon|newspaper=The Officer Down Memorial Page (ODMP)|access-date=2016-11-16}}</ref>\n|-\n|Paul R. Stuewer\n|Investigator\n|New York State Police\n|October 5 2016\n|<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.odmp.org/officer/23008-investigator-paul-r-stuewer|title=Investigator Paul R. Stuewer|newspaper=The Officer Down Memorial Page (ODMP)|access-date=2016-11-29}}</ref>\n|-\n|Douglas Greenwood\n|Captain\n|New York City Police Department\n|December 12 2017\n|<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.officer.com/command-hq/supplies-services/public-awareness/news/20986117/retired-nypd-capt-douglas-greenwood-with-911related-lung-disease-takes-his-own-life|title=Retired NYPD Officer With 9/11-Related Illness Kills Self|website=Officer|language=en|access-date=2019-09-13}}</ref>\n|-\n|William Allee\n|Chief of Detectives\n|New York City Police Department\n|May 24 2018\n|<ref name=\"New York Daily News\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.odmp.org/officer/23692-chief-of-detectives-william-h-allee|title=Chief of Detectives William H. Allee|last=|first=|date=|website=Officer Down Memorial Page|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=July 8, 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n|Luis Alvarez\n|Detective\n|New York City Police Department\n|June 29 2019\n|<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/06/29/obituaries/luis-alvarez-dead.html|title=Luis Alvarez, Champion of 9/11 Responders, Dies at 53|last=|first=|date=June 29, 2019|work=The New York Times|access-date=July 8, 2019}}</ref>\n|}\n\n*\n\n==== Legal ====\nSurviving first responders and their advocates are asserting that their illnesses have resulted from exposure to toxins at Ground Zero. The [[Patrolmen's Benevolent Association of the City of New York]] (PBA) filed a lawsuit to secure benefits for Officer Christopher Hynes, 36. In March 2004 he was diagnosed as having sarcoidosis. However, the NYPD has refused to bestow line-of-duty injury status to him. Hynes had worked for 111 hours at Ground Zero and its vicinity. He claims that he was never given a proper respirator for his work at Ground Zero. He has had difficulty in paying medical bills because of the denial of line-of-duty status. One medical provider sued him for $3,094 for medical bills. The provider eventually settled out of court for $1,625. The PBA noted that firefighters, by contrast, have been given line-of-duty status for their injuries.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nypost.com/seven/06022007/news/regionalnews/pba_sues_to_boot_9_11_air_victim_regionalnews_david_seifman.htm |title=PBA SUES TO BOO$T '9/11 AIR VICTIM' {{!}} By DAVID SEIFMAN {{!}} New York News {{!}} New York City News {{!}} NY News |date=2007-09-29 |access-date=2016-11-16 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070929152919/http://www.nypost.com/seven/06022007/news/regionalnews/pba_sues_to_boot_9_11_air_victim_regionalnews_david_seifman.htm |archivedate=September 29, 2007 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ny1.com/ny1/content/index.jsp?stid=6&aid=70319 |title=NY1: Law Enforcement |date=2007-09-27 |access-date=2016-11-16 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927002945/http://www.ny1.com/ny1/content/index.jsp?stid=6&aid=70319 |archivedate=September 27, 2007 }}</ref>\n\n===Various volunteers===\nHundreds of volunteer firefighters, construction workers, health professionals, clergy, and other individuals descended upon the scene in the days immediately following the attacks. These individuals volunteered directly at the Ground Zero site or cared for traumatized responders. Among individuals in the latter group, newspaper accounts have cited South Carolinian [[Episcopal Church (United States)|Episcopal]] nun, [[Sister Cindy Mahoney|Sister Cindy Mahoney's]] death as a fatality of Ground Zero illness. Mahoney spent several months attending to first responders' spiritual needs. Two weeks prior to her death, she was cut off from her insurance. She choked to death on November 1, 2006, following five years of lung troubles.<ref name=\"sonsname\" /><ref name=\"carlcampanile-kinsuing\" /><ref name=\"davegoldiner\">Dave Goldiner, \"Lung illness take an Angel of Ground Zero.\" \"New York Daily News.\" November 3, 2006, p. 4</ref><ref name=\"emiendo\">Emi Endo, \"Sick 9/11 workers protest at Ground Zero\" Newsday, January 31, 2007 http://www.newsday.com/news/nationworld/nation/am-groundzero0201,0,1528416.story?coll=ny-main-bigpix</ref><ref name=\"sewellchan\">SEWELL CHAN, \"Officer Who Epitomized Ills of Ground Zero Workers Dies\", January 24, 2007, A, Page 17</ref>\n\nSen. [[Hillary Clinton]] on Sister Mahoney and Ground Zero illness: \"We know that so many are now suffering health effects from breathing the toxic air at Ground Zero \u2026 Yet there are still some who doubt the link. By raising attention to her own devastating illness, Sister Mahoney will continue as she did in life, to help those affected by 9/11.\"<ref name=\"davegoldiner\" />\n\n===Communication workers===\nCommunications recovery worker Mark DeBiase, aged 41, died on April 9, 2006, from a Ground Zero illness. He worked without protective gear for restoring communications at the site. \"DeBiase's work was so crucial in emergency workers to communicate that he was shuttled between locations in a military helicopter,\" according to his father, Angelo DeBiase.<ref name=\"carlcampanile-kinsuing\" />\n\n===Janitorial workers===\nManuel Checo is one of many janitors that performed cleanup work who now suffer from ''[[World Trade Center cough]].'' He spent six months at the site. Compounding janitorial workers' troubles, three-quarters of them lack health insurance.<ref name=\"latimes3275974\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://articles.latimes.com/2006/oct/14/nation/na-cleaners14|title=Lost in the Dust of 9/11|last=Barry|first=Ellen|date=2006-10-14|newspaper=Los Angeles Times|language=en-US|issn=0458-3035|access-date=2016-11-16}}</ref>\n\n===Financial district personnel===\nCivil rights attorney Felicia Dunn-Jones, 42, died February 10, 2002, from [[sarcoidosis]]. The city's chief medical examiner belatedly attributed her death to her being engulfed in the dust cloud from the collapse of the Twin Towers, one block from her office.<ref>Maggie Haberman, \"Post-9/11 death is a homicide\", ''New York Post'', May 24, 2007, 4</ref><ref>Maggie Westfeldt, \"One more 9/11 victim to be named on 6th anniversary of attacks\", ''Newsday'', September 8, 2007 http://www.newsday.com/news/local/wire/newyork/ny-bc-ny--anothervictim0908sep08,0,7252878.story</ref>\n\nMayor [[Rudy Giuliani]] acted quickly to \"reopen [[Wall Street]].\" The Wall Street area reopened for business on September 17.\n\n===Educators and students===\nStudents and staff at [[Stuyvesant High School]] returned to the school which lies within one-third of a mile north of the World Trade Center site, while fires were still burning at Ground Zero. Alumni are circulating a petition for greater attention to health problems related to the Ground Zero air.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://asthmamoms.com/worldtradecenterarticles2001.htm |title=AsthmaMoms World Trade Center: Environmental Health Articles 2001 |date=2012-02-02 |access-date=2016-11-16 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120202132450/http://asthmamoms.com/worldtradecenterarticles2001.htm |archivedate=February 2, 2012 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://stuyhealth.blogspot.com/2006_03_01_stuyhealth_archive.html|title=StuyHealth: March 2006|author=StuyHealth|accessdate=June 15, 2015}}</ref> There is a debate over whether the 2002 Class President Amit Friedlander's developing cancer is related to Ground Zero air.\n\nIn addition, the students and staff members at the [[Murry Bergtraum High School]] returned to the building a couple of days after the attack, with the air system in the school severely affected and damaged from the debris and dust from the World Trade Center site (the school is three-quarters of a mile east of the site). Several teachers, particularly from the business department, and students have developed asthma and other breathing problems because of the lack of unpolluted air and the failure to clean the school's central air system thoroughly years after the attack.\n\n==Documentaries==\n*''[[Fallout: The Health Impact of 9/11]]''\n*''[[Dust to Dust: The Health Effects of 9/11]]''\n*''[[Toxic Clouds of 9/11|The Toxic Clouds of 9/11: A Looming Disaster]]''\n*''[[Toxic Legacy]]''\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|New York City}}\n{{Commons category|Health effects arising from the September 11 attacks|health effects arising from the September 11 attacks}}\n{{Wikinewspar2|Obama signs healthcare bill for 9/11 emergency workers|9/11 health care bill passed in US House of Representatives}}\n*[[Casualties of the September 11 attacks]]\n*[[Collapse of the World Trade Center]]\n*[[EPA 9/11 pollution controversy]]\n*[[